<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="163" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,222,499]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,330,355]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[507,734,330,355]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bassleri">
<emphasis box="[507,734,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Cercosaura bassleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to western 
<taxonomicName box="[997,1115,330,355]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="12" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, with its eastern distribution delimited by the 
<collectingRegion box="[344,484,366,391]" country="Uruguay" name="Rio Negro" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Negro River</collectingRegion>
north of the Amazon, and the Madeira river system south of it, occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1361,1432,366,391]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,264,402,427]" name="Colombia" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[278,332,403,426]" name="Peru" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[397,479,402,427]" name="Bolivia" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[497,568,402,427]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1822,1844]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,564,1791]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,554,1800]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Distribution of examined material of Cercosaura bassleri, C. eigenmanni, C. ocellata, and C. schreibersii." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581983/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[625,696,402,427]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[1064,1185,403,427]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1199,1256,403,427]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Acre</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[1320,1433,402,427]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,378,438,463]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bassleri">
<emphasis box="[151,378,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Cercosaura bassleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits terra firme forest, where it is mainly found among leaf litter (Duellman &amp; Salas 1991; Schlüter 
<emphasis box="[543,600,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">et al.</emphasis>
2004; Macedo 
<emphasis box="[774,831,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">et al.</emphasis>
2008).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
